ven and a half years, serving, successively, the Ministries of Lord John Russell, (Whig, 1846-52), Lord Derby (Conservative, 1852), Lord Aberdeen (Whig/Peelite coalition, 1852-55), Lord Palmerston (Whig, 1855-58), and Lord Derby again (1858-59). He was gazetted with the civil K.C.B. in recognition of his lengthy service at Whitehall, in particular his labours during the Russian (Crimean) War. He possessed in abundance both patience and discretion. He stated however that 'When I joined the Admiralty in December 1847, it was under the distinct understanding with Lord Russell, then Prime Minister, and Lord Auckland, the First Lord of the Admiralty, that I was to be entirely free from all political matters.'  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aMaritime History. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / Victorian Era (1837-1901).2bisacsh  aAdmiralty.  aAnti-slavery Patrol.  aBalaklava.  aBaltic Sea.  aBaron Raglan.  aBlack Sea.  aCharles Napier.  aCharles Wood.  aConstantinople.  aCrimean War.  aDockyards.  aFrance.  aJ.W.D. Dundas.  aJames R.G.Graham.  aLord Lyons.  aMalta.  aManning the Navy.  aMediterranean.  aMerseilles.  aPax Britannica.  aPeter Christie.  aPortsmouth.  aR.S.Dundas.  aRoyal Navy.  aSir Alexander Milne.  aSir John Franklin.  aThe Victorian Navy.  aTransport Service.1 aBeeler, John, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781000340839423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781000340839/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles